<h2>West Virginia Incentives & Rebates</h2>

<p>West Virginia offers several incentives that make solar and HVAC investments more attractive for homeowners. The federal solar Investment Tax Credit (ITC) provides a 30% credit on the total cost of solar installations, including equipment, labor, and permits. This credit applies to both residential and commercial installations and can be carried forward if the credit exceeds tax liability in the installation year.</p>

<p>The state provides a property tax exemption for solar energy systems, ensuring that adding solar panels won't increase property tax assessments. This exemption applies to both the solar panels and associated equipment like inverters and battery storage systems. Additionally, West Virginia offers sales tax exemptions on solar equipment purchases, reducing the overall system cost by 6-6.5% depending on local tax rates.</p>

<p>Appalachian Power offers net metering programs that credit solar system owners for excess electricity fed back into the grid. Under current net metering rules, customers receive retail rate credits for solar production, effectively using the grid as a battery. The utility also periodically offers rebate programs for energy-efficient HVAC systems, though these programs vary by year and available funding.</p>

<p>For HVAC systems, federal tax credits are available for qualifying heat pumps, geothermal systems, and other high-efficiency equipment. The Inflation Reduction Act expanded these credits significantly, offering up to \$2,000 for heat pump installations and up to \$8,000 for electrical panel upgrades needed to support new equipment. Low-income households may qualify for additional rebates and financing assistance through weatherization programs administered by the state.</p>

<p>Local utility programs sometimes offer additional rebates for energy-efficient upgrades. Mountaineer Gas Company and other regional utilities occasionally provide rebates for high-efficiency heating systems, and some municipalities offer property tax abatements for renewable energy installations. Homeowners should check with their specific utility provider and local government for current incentive availability.</p>

